# eRPC multi-provider proxy for Optimism mainnet (chain 10).
#
# **Current shape: 2-of-3 consensus across publicnode + tenderly + self-hosted.**
#
# Iteration history:
#  - #130 deploy: tried publicnode + official-op + ankr-op. official-op
#    (mainnet.optimism.io) â†’ HTTP 429 from Mac mini IP. ankr-op needs
#    paid API key. Dropped both, swapped in tenderly + 1rpc.
#  - #138 deploy: publicnode + tenderly + 1rpc (2-of-3, threshold=2).
#  - #144 deploy: bumped to 3-of-3 after Codex retro-audit caught the
#    CF-collusion poisoning attack (2 CF-fronted upstreams returning
#    the same forged view satisfy quorum 2-of-3 â†’ poison authoritative).
#  - **2026-05-20 (this PR)**: dropped 1rpc-op entirely. eRPC's URL
#    parser strips the `/op` path segment from `https://1rpc.io/op`,
#    sending requests to 1rpc's landing page instead of the OP RPC.
#    Confirmed via the parsed-config dump:
#      "endpoint":"https://1rpc.io#redacted=..." (no path)
#    1rpc consistently failed â†’ `n/a = ErrUpstreamsExhausted` on every
#    consensus call â†’ 3-of-3 was unsatisfiable â†’ driver couldn't boot.
#
# **Final config: 3 upstreams, agreementThreshold=2 (2-of-3 quorum).**
# Considered 3-of-3 strict during the self-hosted onboarding window
# (header comment iteration 144 below); reverted to 2-of-3 because
# 3-of-3 was unsatisfiable under self-hosted's normal tip-drift. The
# threat-model exposition below (lines 145-153) describes 2-of-3
# quorum: a single hostile upstream cannot satisfy quorum because the
# remaining 2 (across 2 distinct DNS providers) would dispute.
#
#   publicnode-op       optimism-rpc.publicnode.com    Allnodes
#                                                       DNS: Cloudflare
#                                                       CA: Let's Encrypt
#   tenderly-op         optimism.gateway.tenderly.co   Tenderly
#                                                       DNS: Google Cloud
#                                                       CA: ZeroSSL/Sectigo
#   ophis-op-node-self  Aleph VM via Tailscale         Ours, fully synced
#                       100.77.53.81:8545              op-reth v1.10.2 +
#                                                       op-node v1.18.0
#                                                       (Phase 4, prov.
#                                                       2026-05-13, 1.9 TB)
#
# **Threat-model: 3-of-3 over 3 fully-independent failure domains is
# the strongest posture achievable. The prior 2-of-3 (with 2
# CF-correlated upstreams) was poisonable under CF compromise. The
# 2-of-2 interim (publicnode + tenderly) was DoS-not-poisoning but
# couldn't get back to 3-of-3 because the only 3rd free provider
# (1rpc-op) had a broken URL-parse and tenderly's free public tier
# rate-limited `eth_getBalance`. Self-hosting closes both problems:**
#
#  - Cloudflare DNS compromise â†’ only publicnode is hijacked. tenderly
#    on Google DNS returns the real answer â†’ dispute â†’ returnError â†’
#    driver stops, does NOT settle against forged state.
#  - Google DNS compromise â†’ only tenderly is hijacked. publicnode on
#    CF DNS returns the real answer â†’ dispute â†’ returnError â†’ safe.
#  - Both DNS providers compromised simultaneously: requires nation-
#    state class control over both CF AND Google DNS infrastructure.
#    Out of scope of the threat model.
#  - Both upstreams happen to return the same answer: that IS the
#    canonical chain state (publicnode and tenderly are independent
#    operators; both seeing identical block data is the correct case).
#
# Availability cost: any single-upstream blip = fail. Same posture as
# the broken 3-of-3 we replaced; no regression. Driver tolerates via
# bootstrap-retry + autopilot retry budget. If a 3rd non-CF upstream
# becomes available we can add it (and bump back to 3-of-3 if 2 of 3
# are still distinct-DNS).
#
# Trade-off accepted: "we'd rather not settle than settle against
# forged state." Standard posture for any DEX moving real money.
#
# Rationale (replace-not-expand; mirroring the HL audit reasoning):
#  - N=3 keeps the 2-of-3 consensus invariant defensible. Expanding N to >3 with
#    eRPC's random sampling (maxParticipants:3) silently weakens the threat
#    model to "attacker needs â‰Ą2 of N" â€” see HL config for the math.
#  - All 3 are uniformly unauthenticated HTTPS / public-tier. No MEV-searcher
#    overlap (Bloxroute / Blocknative / Flashbots-style providers excluded â€”
#    same uniform policy as HL eRPC).
#  - Per-block consensus equality is sound on OP: post-Bedrock, the L2's
#    block contents are deterministic per L2 block number; only tip drift on
#    "which block is latest" varies, which `enforceHighestBlock` handles.
#
# Endpoint exposed: http://rpc-proxy:4000/main/evm/10

logLevel: info

projects:
  - id: main

    networks:
      - architecture: evm
        evm:
          chainId: 10
          integrity:
            enforceHighestBlock: true
            enforceNonNullTaggedBlocks: true
        # Consensus failsafe: defeats fork-view-poisoning on state-reads.
        # Each free provider is unauthenticated HTTPS â€” a hostile provider
        # (or MITM via CA compromise / DNS hijack) could otherwise serve a
        # self-consistent fork that the autopilot signs settlements against.
        # 2-of-3 agreement on the methods that drive solver behavior closes
        # that hole.
        failsafe:
          # Critical reads: state-dependent calls that gate solver behavior
          # and settlement validity. eth_getTransactionByHash is included
          # because the response carries forkable fields (blockHash,
          # blockNumber); a hostile upstream on the non-consensus "*" path
          # could otherwise mislead the autopilot's settlement-watcher.
          # Network-level timeout 12s gives 2s headroom over the slowest
          # upstream-level timeout (~10s) â€” sharp-edges follow-up #6.
          #
          # Method list (Codex retro-audit, 2026-05-20):
          # - `eth_estimateGas`: a forged-low estimate yields txs that
          #   revert (gas-only loss bounded by the 5 gwei cap from #131,
          #   but still budget-wasteful).
          # - `eth_feeHistory`: feeds into EIP-1559 fee predictions;
          #   manipulation lets a hostile upstream steer submission gas.
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening â€” DROPPED `eth_getBlockByNumber` and
          # `eth_getBlockByHash` from strict consensus. They were the
          # dominant source of `ErrConsensusDispute` (95+ disputes in
          # 2-minute windows post-deploy) because the two upstreams hold
          # slightly different views of `"latest"` at any wall-clock
          # microsecond â€” pure tip-drift, no security signal. Block reads
          # by NUMBER (not tag) would be deterministic but the driver
          # mostly queries `"latest"`. Removing these methods from
          # consensus drops to the `*` catch-all rule below (retry, no
          # consensus). Per-block-content integrity is still enforced
          # via `enforceHighestBlock: true` + `enforceNonNullTaggedBlocks:
          # true` at the network level above. Settlement-integrity
          # methods (`eth_call`, `eth_getLogs`, `eth_getTransactionReceipt`,
          # `eth_getTransactionByHash`) keep 2-of-3 consensus.
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening (2) â€” DROPPED `eth_getBalance` from strict
          # consensus too. Tenderly's free public Gateway hit per-IP
          # rate-limit (HTTP 429 ErrEndpointCapacityExceeded) under
          # sustained polling from driver+orderbook+autopilot. (Residual
          # since closed in 2026-05-20 evening (3) below.)
          #
          # 2026-05-20 evening (3) â€” ADDED self-hosted ophis-op-node-self
          # as the 3rd upstream. VM1 (Aleph `ophis-op-node` at
          # Tailscale 100.77.53.81) runs op-reth v1.10.2 + op-node v1.18.0,
          # fully synced, controlled by us. This removes the Tenderly
          # rate-limit bottleneck (we poll our own node freely) AND adds
          # a 3rd fully-independent failure domain (Aleph network â€” not
          # CF, not Google).
          #
          # Restored: `eth_getBalance` back to strict consensus. The
          # rate-limit reason for demotion is no longer a constraint.
          #
          # Bumped: agreementThreshold 2 â†’ 3 (every upstream must agree).
          # Threat model now (3 distinct DNS/operator/network):
          #   - CF DNS compromise: hijacks only publicnode â†’ tenderly +
          #     self return truth â†’ dispute â†’ returnError â†’ safe
          #   - Google DNS compromise: hijacks only tenderly â†’ publicnode
          #     + self â†’ safe
          #   - Aleph compromise (someone gets into our VM): hijacks only
          #     self â†’ publicnode + tenderly â†’ safe
          #   - All 3 simultaneously: requires owning CF + Google + Aleph
          #     infrastructures â†’ nation-state++ class, out of scope.
          #
          # This is the strongest posture achievable today. The CF-DNS
          # concentration residual (documented through #144â†’#148 iterations)
          # is now fully closed.
          # 2026-05-20 â€” root-cause REVISED during task #112 investigation.
          # The Phase 3.1 swap failure was NOT a containerâ†’Tailscale
          # reachability issue (a one-shot alpine container on the same
          # docker network successfully called 100.77.53.81:8545). The
          # actual cause: eRPC's punishMisbehavior policy was kicking the
          # self-hosted upstream into a 5-min sit-out every time it had
          # minor tip-drift (5 disputes in 10min â†’ punishment). With OP's
          # 2s block time, tip-drift between independently-operated
          # indexers is the natural state â€” disputeThreshold:5 punishes
          # normal operation.
          #
          # ============================================================
          # 2026-05-20 (task #119) â€” SPLIT disputeThreshold BY METHOD.
          # ============================================================
          #
          # Why the single-bucket threshold:100 was unsafe to keep:
          # a single global threshold of 100 means a hostile upstream
          # can return up to 99 forged answers per 10-min window on the
          # most security-critical methods (eth_call, eth_getBalance)
          # before catching a 5-min sit-out â€” sustained ~95% DoS duty
          # cycle on the path that gates settlement. Phase 4 audit N1
          # (Codex + sharp-edges, 2026-05-20) flagged this as
          # defense-in-depth-required pre-meaningful-TVL.
          #
          # Split into two consensus blocks by threat surface:
          #
          # **Block A â€” deterministic-state methods (LOW threshold)**:
          # eth_call, eth_getBalance, eth_getCode, eth_getStorageAt.
          # These are pure state lookups at a specified block tag.
          #
          # `enforceHighestBlock: true` (set at the network level above)
          # gates routing to only-fully-caught-up upstreams â€” it does
          # NOT coordinate the participants to query a specific block
          # number. Two upstreams 1 block apart on "latest" will still
          # return two state snapshots; only the behind-tip one gets
          # routed-around. Drift IS real on this bucket.
          # `eth_getTransactionCount` is deliberately NOT in Block A:
          # the `pending` block tag is mempool-dependent, and the
          # driver's submission mempool is pinned to publicnode-op
          # alone â€” the self-hosted op-node will not see pending txs
          # before the sequencer gossips them back, so EIP-7702
          # delegation-setup ceremonies (90s of pending-tag polling)
          # would cordon self-hosted within seconds of every boot.
          # Moved to Block B where threshold:100 absorbs that burst.
          #
          # threshold:60 catches hostile sustained divergence ~1.7Ă— faster
          # than the previous threshold:100 while preserving 3Ă— headroom
          # over the live ~20 disputes/10min baseline (driven primarily
          # by ophis-op-node-self tip-drift on "latest" tags). Sharp-
          # edges finding 1 (2026-05-20): the 1.5Ă— headroom of threshold:30
          # was insufficient for bootstrap-burst + OP-sequencer-hiccup
          # scenarios where all 3 upstreams snap back to consensus at
          # different microseconds. Threshold:60 is the floor; raise to
          # 100 (and accept the DoS-window cost) only if false-ejection
          # alerts fire repeatedly on a healthy upstream over a 24h
          # window.
          #
          # **Block B â€” tip-lag-tolerant observation methods (HIGH
          # threshold)**: eth_getLogs, eth_getTransactionReceipt,
          # eth_getTransactionByHash, eth_estimateGas, eth_feeHistory,
          # eth_getTransactionCount.
          # These have natural disagreement floors driven by indexer
          # propagation lag near the chain tip (e.g. just-landed
          # Settlement txs may not be indexed by all upstreams
          # simultaneously; estimateGas has provider-implementation
          # variance; feeHistory percentiles differ slightly between
          # providers; getTransactionCount with `pending` tag is
          # mempool-dependent and only the publicnode-op mempool is
          # authoritative for our submission path). threshold:100
          # absorbs this baseline drift while still catching sustained
          # malicious answers â€” each forged dispute still triggers
          # consensus failure â†’ returnError â†’ driver fails closed at
          # request time. The threshold only controls whether we keep
          # retrying that upstream over time.
          #
          # **Block C** is the existing catch-all retry (no consensus).
          #
          # Empirical baseline (live OP mainnet eRPC, ~1h window
          # 2026-05-20 evening):
          #   eth_call:                      2.09% dispute rate
          #   eth_feeHistory:                1.64% dispute rate
          #   eth_getTransactionReceipt:     0.25% dispute rate
          #   eth_getLogs:                   0.12% dispute rate
          # The Block A threshold of 60 leaves 3Ă— headroom for eth_call
          # (the most-disputed method in that bucket). Operational reality
          # test: redeploy â†’ monitor erpc_upstream_cordoned for false
          # ejections in the first hour. If false-ejection fires more
          # than once per 30 minutes on a healthy upstream, raise to 100
          # (matching Block B) and accept the DoS-window cost.
          #
          # **Pairs with new Prometheus alerts** (observability/alerts.yml):
          # - OphisOpErpcUpstreamCordoned (per-upstream sat-out detection)
          # - OphisOpErpcUpstreamBlockHeadLagging (chronic-lag root cause)
          # - OphisOpErpcCordonMetricAbsent (silent-monitoring-gap guard)

          # === Block A: Deterministic-state methods (LOW threshold) ===
          - matchMethod: "eth_call|eth_getBalance|eth_getCode|eth_getStorageAt"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            consensus:
              maxParticipants: 3
              # 2-of-3 across fully-independent failure domains:
              # - publicnode-op (Allnodes; CF DNS)
              # - tenderly-op (Tenderly; Google Cloud DNS)
              # - ophis-op-node-self (Aleph VM, self-hosted via Tailscale)
              agreementThreshold: 2
              disputeBehavior: returnError
              lowParticipantsBehavior: returnError
              preferNonEmpty: true
              # No `ignoreFields` here â€” see HL eRPC Codex Cyber finding #1.
              # Allowing field-level skip lets a hostile upstream forge the
              # skipped field while matching every other field; consensus
              # passes spuriously.
              punishMisbehavior:
                # TIGHT threshold for security-critical state lookups.
                # 3Ă— headroom over the empirical 20 disputes/10min
                # baseline on eth_call. A hostile upstream catches a 5-min
                # sit-out after 60 forged answers (vs 100 in the old
                # single-bucket config) â€” 1.7Ă— DoS-window reduction on
                # the settlement-gating path. Sharp-edges (2026-05-20)
                # bumped this from 30 â†’ 60 to absorb bootstrap-burst
                # scenarios where 3 upstreams snap back to consensus at
                # different microseconds during driver redeploy.
                disputeThreshold: 60
                disputeWindow: 10m
                sitOutPenalty: 5m

          # === Block B: Tip-lag-sensitive observation methods (HIGH threshold) ===
          #
          # 2026-05-21 follow-up: REMOVED eth_getTransactionReceipt from
          # the Block B consensus regex. The 200-threshold bump on 2026-05-20
          # was not enough â€” `OphisOpErpcUpstreamCordoned` fired 3 more
          # times within hours of the deploy, each time accumulating
          # ~12,000 `response_type="empty"` misbehavior events on
          # ophis-op-node-self before the eviction. Root cause is
          # structural: op-reth's receipt indexing is materially slower
          # than publicnode + tenderly's hosted indexers (likely they
          # serve from a denormalized receipt cache rather than
          # re-traversing the trie). During Settlement-broadcast bursts
          # the driver polls fresh receipts every block tick; self-hosted
          # returns empty for a few seconds longer than the others, ends
          # up the lone dissenter on every poll, and the dispute counter
          # accumulates faster than ANY threshold we could tune around
          # without effectively disabling the policy.
          #
          # Trade-off accepted: eth_getTransactionReceipt now falls
          # through to Block C (catch-all retry, no consensus). The
          # protection we lose is "a hostile upstream forging
          # receipt-exists/receipt-missing to mislead the autopilot
          # settlement-watcher". The watcher cross-checks via eth_call
          # against the on-chain Settlement contract (which IS still
          # under Block A consensus at threshold:60), so a forged
          # receipt alone cannot cause settlement-state divergence â€”
          # only the eth_call against Settlement's `filledAmount` is
          # authoritative. Receipt confirmation is best-effort UX, not
          # a security primitive.
          #
          # If a future version of op-reth speeds up receipt indexing
          # (or we switch to op-erigon / op-geth on the VM), re-add
          # eth_getTransactionReceipt to this regex and bump back.
          - matchMethod: "eth_getLogs|eth_getTransactionByHash|eth_estimateGas|eth_feeHistory|eth_getTransactionCount"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            consensus:
              maxParticipants: 3
              agreementThreshold: 2
              disputeBehavior: returnError
              lowParticipantsBehavior: returnError
              preferNonEmpty: true
              punishMisbehavior:
                # 200 was sized to absorb the receipt burst â€” without
                # that method here, the remaining members have much
                # lower dispute floors, but we keep 100 (the original
                # value) as a defensive cap. Drift between publicnode +
                # tenderly + self on `eth_getLogs` near tip is ~10
                # disputes / 10min historically; threshold:100 gives 10Ă—
                # headroom.
                disputeThreshold: 100
                disputeWindow: 10m
                sitOutPenalty: 5m

          # === Block C: Catch-all retry (no consensus) ===
          # Block-stream polling, balance reads on non-consensus paths.
          # Tx submission routes via driver's pinned [[submission.mempool]]
          # block (single endpoint, nonce-coherent).
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 12s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 150ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

    # OP block time is ~2s post-Bedrock; align tip-block tracking.
    upstreamDefaults:
      evm:
        statePollerInterval: 5s
        statePollerDebounce: 1s

    upstreams:
      - id: publicnode-op
        endpoint: https://optimism-rpc.publicnode.com
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

      - id: tenderly-op
        # Non-CF anchor (Google Cloud DNS). Tenderly's public gateway
        # has no documented rate cap; we measured ~270ms first-byte
        # which is comfortable headroom. If Tenderly tightens this
        # endpoint behind a key in the future, swap-procedure is in
        # docs/operations/op-erpc-runbook.md.
        endpoint: https://optimism.gateway.tenderly.co
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

      - id: ophis-op-node-self
        # Self-hosted op-reth + op-node on Aleph VM "ophis-op-node"
        # (Tailscale IP 100.77.53.81, public 46.247.131.211:24718 SSH).
        # Phase 4 â€” Aleph VMs in project_ophis.md has the full setup
        # history (provisioned 2026-05-13 with 1.9 TB after the 1.1 TB
        # disk-full miss, snapshot from datadirs.optimism.io, op-reth
        # v1.10.2 + op-node v1.18.0).
        #
        # Reach path: Mac mini docker bridge â†’ host networking â†’
        # Tailscale interface â†’ wireguard â†’ VM1's tailscale0 â†’
        # iptables NAT rule (allows source 100.100.107.110 and
        # 100.115.232.82) â†’ docker-proxy â†’ op-reth 127.0.0.1:8545.
        #
        # Latency: ~50ms RTT (Tailscale wireguard).
        #
        # Failure modes:
        # - VM1 down: this upstream returns connection refused â†’
        #   participant timeout. With agreementThreshold: 2, the
        #   remaining 2 (publicnode + tenderly) form quorum if they
        #   agree â€” settlement continues. If those 2 ALSO disagree
        #   simultaneously (unlikely unless real network split), we
        #   drop below threshold â†’ returnError â†’ driver pauses until
        #   any 2 of 3 recover agreement.
        # - Tailscale relay/wireguard hiccup: same as above.
        # - Public IP changes (Aleph reprovision): UPDATE THIS ENDPOINT.
        #
        # No DNS dependency â€” IP-pinned because container DNS doesn't
        # resolve Tailscale MagicDNS by default.
        endpoint: http://100.77.53.81:8545
        failsafe:
          - matchMethod: "*"
            timeout:
              duration: 8s
            retry:
              maxAttempts: 3
              delay: 200ms
              backoffMaxDelay: 1s
              backoffFactor: 1.5
              jitter: 50ms

